      "output": "At its most basic level, **water** is a transparent, odorless, and tasteless liquid that is essential for all known forms of life. \n\nTo truly understand what water is, we can look at it through a few different lenses:\n\n### 1. The Chemical View\nChemically, water is a molecule made up of three atoms: **two hydrogen atoms bonded to one oxygen atom**. This is why its chemical formula is **$H_2O$**. \n* **The \"Magnet\" Effect:** Water molecules have a unique shape—like Mickey Mouse ears—which makes one side slightly positive (the hydrogens) and the other side slightly negative (the oxygen). Because of this, water molecules love to stick to each other and to other substances. This property makes water an incredible \"universal solvent,\" meaning it can dissolve more substances than any other liquid.\n\n### 2. The States of Matter\nWater is one of the few substances on Earth that naturally exists in three distinct forms depending on the temperature:\n* **Liquid:** The standard form we drink, swim in, and rain from the sky.\n* **Solid (Ice):** Formed when water freezes at or below 0°C (32°F). *Fun fact: Ice is less dense than liquid water, which is why ice floats instead of sinking.*\n* **Gas (Vapor/Steam):** Formed when water boils or evaporates. Water vapor is invisible in the air.\n\n### 3. The Ecological and Geological View\nWater covers about **71% of the Earth's surface**, primarily in oceans and seas (which hold about 96.5% of all Earth's water). It is constantly moving in a cycle—evaporating from the earth, forming clouds, falling as rain or snow (precipitation), and flowing back into rivers and oceans. This is known as the **water cycle**.\n\n### 4. The Biological View\nWater is the fundamental building block of life. \n* **Human bodies:** Adult human bodies are made up of about 60% water. \n* **Function:** Water regulates our internal body temperature, lubricates joints, flushes out waste, and acts as the medium in which all the chemical reactions of metabolism take place. Without water, humans can only survive for about 3 to 5 days.\n\n**In short:** Water is the lifeblood of our planet. It shapes our geography, regulates our climate, and is"
